Getting Started: Using GitHub Desktop for Version Control
=========================================================

This guide walks you through the Git workflow using the GitHub Desktop application.

PART 1 – Clone a Repository
----------------------------
1. Open GitHub Desktop.

2. Go to: "File" → "Clone Repository."

3. Select the "URL" tab.

4. Paste the repository URL:
   https://github.com/vmahan1998/GitHub_Basic_Skills.git
   
5. Choose a local path and click “Clone”.

PART 2 – Create a Branch
-------------------------
1. In GitHub Desktop, click on the “Current Branch” dropdown.

2. Click “New Branch”.

3. Enter a name for your branch (e.g., `add-message`).

4. Click “Create Branch”.

PART 3 – Make a Change
-----------------------
1. In File Explorer (Windows) or Finder (Mac), navigate to the local folder you cloned.

2. Open the file `EDIT_ME.txt` in a text editor (e.g., Notepad, VSCode).

3. Add a line with your name and message at the end like:
   "Vanessa: This is my first GitHub Desktop edit!"
   
4. Save the file.

PART 4 – Commit and Push Your Change
-------------------------------------
1. Return to GitHub Desktop.

2. The file change will be listed in the “Changes” tab.

3. In the “Summary” field, enter a commit message:
   "Add message to guestbook"
4. Click “Commit to add-message”.

5. Click “Push origin” (top bar) to upload your branch to GitHub.

NOTE:
-----
This is a personal project workflow for practicing Git basics to build confidence in making and tracking changes.
